Author::::Hosta_Madosta
DateTime::::2016-03-08T20:33:34Z
More information on Fessenheim (from French and German Wikipedia):The powerplant is situated on a seismic faultline (Oberrheingraben). According to Swiss studies, earthquakes with a magnitude of 6.0 to 6.5 occur about once in 100 years, earthquakes of 6.5 to 7.0 once in a thousand years (case in point being the earthquake that destroyed Basel in 1356, the strongest earthquake ever registered in Northwestern Europe). This is far less strong than the Fukushima earthquake (9.0), but Fessenheim would be much nearer to the epicenter (being right on the faultline). The foundations of the powerplant are 1.5 m thick (the thinnest foundations of all French nuclear powerplants; Fukushima's foundations were 7 m thick). It is built next to the Grand Canal of Alsace without sufficient protection against a dam break (the canal being subjected to seismic risks just as well). It sits on the Upper Rhine aquifer which supplies about 3 million people with drinking water. In a radius of 30 km live a population of 930,000 (among them, my parents).I won't be sorry when it's gone... if it finally happens (French politicians have been promising it for years).



